> Okay, so there's technically no vodka in this recipe, but that can be our secret. The combination of creamy tomato sauce and salty pancetta is flavorful enough without it! Serve straight from the skillet for a way easier cleanup.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Mince or grate the @garlic{4%cloves}. Roughly chop the @parsley{1/4%ounce}. Add the @rigatoni pasta{12%ounce} to the boiling water. Cook ~{9-11%minutes}, until al dente. Drain.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large tall-sided pan over medium-high heat. Add the @pancetta{4%ounce} to the pan. Cook, tossing, for ~{4-5%minutes}, until crispy and golden brown. Remove the pancetta with a #slotted spoon{}, reserving the oil. Place onto a #paper towel{}.

Heat the same pan over medium heat. Add the garlic to the reserved pancetta oil. Cook ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant. Whisk in the @flour{2%tablespoon}, and cook another ~{1%minute}. Slowly whisk in the @milk{2%box}, adding a little bit at a time, until fully incorporated. Bring to a boil. Cook ~{1-2%minutes}, until thickened. Remove from heat, and stir in the @parmesan cheese{1/2%cup}. Once melted, stir in the @crushed tomatoes{1%box} and @spinach{5%ounce}(to wilt). Season generously with salt and @pepper{}.

> TIP: If the sauce isn't hot enough to wilt the spinach, return pan to medium heat.

Preheat the broiler to high or the #oven{} to 500. Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in the #microwave{} (or a small pan). Toss the @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup} and half the parsley into the melted butter. Season with salt and pepper.

Broil the pasta: Toss the pasta, pancetta, and remaining parsley into the sauce. Season with salt and pepper. Sprinkle the panko mixture over the pasta. Transfer to the oven to broil ~{2-3%minutes}, watching carefully, until golden brown.

Finish: Serve the rigatoni "a la vodka" straight out of the pan and enjoy!